context: By the mid-7th century, <a0_0><b5_0>English and Irish missionaries<b5_0/> set out to convert the Frisians<a0_0/>. <a1_0>The pope appointed their leader, Willibrordus, bishop of the Frisians<a1_0/>. The tenure of Willibrordus is generally considered to be the beginning of the Bishopric of Utrecht. In 723, the <a2_0>Frankish leader <b6_0>Charles Martel<b6_0/> bestowed the fortress in Utrecht and the surrounding lands as the base of the bishops<a2_0/>. From then on Utrecht became one of the most influential seats of power for the Roman Catholic Church in the Netherlands. The archbishops of Utrecht were based at the uneasy northern border of the Carolingian Empire. In addition, the city of Utrecht had competition from the nearby trading centre <b7_0>Dorestad<b7_0/>. <a3_0>After the fall of Dorestad around 850, Utrecht became one of the most important cities in the Netherlands<a3_0/>. The importance of <a4_0>Utrecht as a centre of Christianity is illustrated by the election of the Utrecht-born Adriaan Florenszoon Boeyens as pope in 1522<a4_0/> (the last non-Italian pope before John Paul II).
